From: Mark Turner "Categories and Analogies" 
=============================================
in Helman, D.H. (Ed.) (1988), Analogical reasoning.
   Dordrecht: Kluwer Academic Publishers.


MENTAL METAPHORS (presented as examples)

p.10:

-- Books are embalmed minds
-- Wrinkles are the deathbed wherein women bury their illusions
-- Insanity is often the logic of an accurate mind overtaxed
-- The body is the socket of the soul

p.12:

-- A proverb is the child of experience
-- Admiration is the daughter of ignorance
-- Man is a sun; and the senses are his planets
-- Everyone is a moon, and has a dark side which he never shows to anybody
-- I am a parcel of vain strivings tied by a chance bond together
-- Every extreme attitude is a flight from the self
-- Convictions are mortgages on the mind

p.13:

-- Religion is a disease, but it is a noble disease

NB: The "Everyone is a moon, ..." example is attributed to Mark Twain, e.g. by

    Brians, Paul (2003),
    Common Errors in English Usage.
    Franklin, Beedle & Associates, Inc.
